        <p><strong>Where GPTZero wins:</strong> verifying that a piece of writing was authored by a human (educators, publishers, HR). <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> generating organic traffic. Pick by the job, not the brand.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is GPTZero?</h2>
        <p>GPTZero is an AI content detector founded in 2023 by Edward Tian, then a senior at Princeton. The product launched as a side project for educators trying to spot ChatGPT-generated student essays and exploded into the most-used AI detector on the internet — 2.5M+ users across schools, newsrooms, courts, and HR teams.</p>

        <p>The detection model is built on two linguistic signals:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Perplexity</strong> — how predictable each word is given the surrounding context. AI-generated text has lower perplexity than human writing.</li>
          <li><strong>Burstiness</strong> — variation in sentence structure and length. Humans write in bursts; AI writes uniformly.</li>
        </ol>

        <p>GPTZero combines these signals with classifier models trained on human-vs-AI corpora and outputs a probability score that the content was AI-generated. The interface highlights sentences flagged as AI in red.</p>

        <p>What GPTZero is <em>not</em>: an SEO tool. The detector does nothing to help your content rank — and Google has explicitly said it does not care whether content is AI or human, only whether it's helpful.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>GPTZero raised $13.5M Series A in 2024 led by Footwork. The company has ~30 employees and reports 2.5M+ users globally. Edward Tian remains CEO. Revenue comes primarily from education-sector subscriptions and enterprise licensing for verification workflows.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">GPTZero features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>
        <p>The feature surface is narrow by design. Here's what each does.</p>

        <h3>1. Document scan</h3>
        <p>Paste text or upload a document. GPTZero returns a probability score (0–100%) that the content was AI-generated, plus a verdict bucket: "Likely AI", "Mixed", "Likely human". Documents up to 50,000 characters on Professional. Supports .docx, .pdf, .txt.</p>

        <h3>2. Sentence-level highlights</h3>
        <p>The most useful feature. Each sentence is highlighted on a gradient from green (human) to red (AI), so you can see exactly which passages triggered the flag. Premium and above. Free tier shows only the document-level score.</p>

        <h3>3. Source Origin</h3>
        <p>GPTZero attempts to identify which AI model produced the content (GPT-4, GPT-5, Claude, Gemini, Llama). Accuracy on this is mixed — 60–70% for raw model output, much lower for edited or chained-model content.</p>

        <h3>4. Classroom Mode (Origin)</h3>
        <p>Integrates with Google Docs and Microsoft Word. Tracks the full writing history of a document — keystroke patterns, paste events, time per sentence — to verify human authorship process, not just the final output. Genuinely useful for educators.</p>

        <h3>5. API</h3>
        <p>Available on Premium and Professional. Rate-limited but sufficient for most content workflows. Enterprise customers get higher limits and SLAs.</p>

